PSEUDOCODE
==========

Initialize USART2 TX + RX on PA2, PA3 (AF1)
Initialize SysTick

Send welcome message over UART

Loop forever:
    Poll RXNE flag on USART2->ISR
    If RXNE set:
        Read byte from RDR
        Echo byte back
        Match byte against command table:
            'b' -> switch to BLINK mode   -> send "Mode: Blink\r\n"
            'p' -> switch to BREATHE mode -> send "Mode: Breathe\r\n"
            'f' -> blink faster           -> send "Faster\r\n"
            's' -> blink slower           -> send "Slower\r\n"
            '?' -> send help string
            any other -> send "Unknown command\r\n"

    If BLINK mode:
        Non-blocking LED toggle at current blink_interval

    If BREATHE mode:
        Non-blocking duty ramp on TIM2 CCR1

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA2  ->  USART2_TX (AF1) - transmit to terminal
PA3  ->  USART2_RX (AF1) - receive from terminal
PA5  ->  LED output / TIM2_CH1 AF2 depending on mode
PC13 ->  Not used this program (commands come via UART instead)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

USART2 (Universal Synchronous/Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter)
|-------------|------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register    | Field      | Description                                                                                       |
|-------------|------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| USART2->CR1 | bit2 RE    | Receiver Enable. Enables the RX path. Set alongside TE before UE.                                 |
| USART2->ISR | bit5 RXNE  | RX Not Empty. Set by hardware when a byte has been received into RDR and is ready to read.        |
| USART2->ISR | bit3 ORE   | Overrun Error. Set if a new byte arrives before RDR was read. Must be cleared or receiver stalls. |
| USART2->RDR | bits[8:0]  | Receive Data Register. Read this to get the received byte. Reading clears RXNE automatically.     |
| USART2->ICR | bit3 ORECF | Overrun Error Clear Flag. Write 1 to clear ORE in ISR.                                            |
|-------------|------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

GPIOA (General-Purpose Input/Output Port A)
|-------------|---------------------|------------------------------------|
| Register    | Field               | Description                        |
|-------------|---------------------|------------------------------------|
| GPIOA->AFRL | bits[15:12] for PA3 | AF1 = 0b0001 for USART2_RX on PA3. |
|-------------|---------------------|------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Overrun error stalls the receiver permanently. If our main loop spends too
  long doing something and two bytes arrive back-to-back before RDR is read, ORE
  sets. With ORE set, RXNE never sets again and the receiver appears
  dead. Always check and clear ORE before checking RXNE, as
  `usart2_receive_byte()` does here. This is the single most common UART polling
  bug.

* PA3 MODER must be set to AF. A common oversight is configuring TX (PA2)
  correctly but leaving PA3 in the default analog mode. The receiver works
  electrically but the signal never reaches the USART peripheral. Both pins need
  MODER = 10 and the correct AFRL entry.

* Reading RDR twice. RXNE clears the moment we read RDR. If we read RDR a second
  time before the next byte arrives, we get 0x00 or stale data. Read it exactly
  once per RXNE event.

* Terminal local echo vs firmware echo. Most terminals have a local echo
  setting. If both the terminal and the firmware echo the character, we see
  every keystroke doubled. Disable local echo in the terminal
  (in minicom: Ctrl-A E to toggle) and rely on the firmware echo instead.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* Polling RXNE is fine at low data rates. At 115200 baud, one byte arrives every
  ~87µs. As long as our main loop iteration is well under 87µs, polling catches
  every byte. The moment we add delay_ms() calls or heavier processing inside
  the loop, we risk overruns. That is the motivation for interrupt-driven RX in
  Program 13, where the ISR catches the byte the instant it arrives regardless
  of what the main loop is doing.

* The command table pattern scales well. The switch/case chain here is simple
  and readable for a small command set. For a larger command set (10+ commands),
  a table of {char cmd, void(*handler)(void)} function pointers is cleaner and
  avoids a growing chain. That pattern is worth knowing but the swithc/case
  version is perfectly adequate for embedded debug interfaces. The if/else-if
  version is also a good alternative in this case.

* This program is the interactive companion to everything that follows. From
  here, instead of waiting for an LED to blink to verify behavior, we can send a
  character and get a response over UART. Programs 14 onwards (ADC, DMA, RTC)
  will stream real data back through this same UART interface, turning the
  terminal into a live instrument readout.
